    "title": "What We Fixed Today: Layout, Code Blocks, and the Static Blog Pipeline",
    "slug": "what-we-fixed-today-layout-code-blocks-and-the-static-blog-pipeline",
    "content": "<p>Today was a maintenance and polish day. We did not ship a new feature. We hunted three visible problems that were making the blog feel unpolished, fixed them, and then closed a smaller set of follow-ups that had been quietly degrading the underlying workflow. This post is the running log of those changes, written so the decisions stay readable later.</p>\n<h2>The Three Visible Problems</h2>\n<p>Three things were wrong on the published site:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>the table of contents sidebar and the series navigation panel were overlapping and both too narrow;</li>\n<li>long code blocks in post content could not be scrolled horizontally on small screens, which meant wide code examples were clipped;</li>\n<li>the social floating footer was inconsistent across pages.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>These were not aesthetic preferences. Each one was a small but real usability defect.</p>\n<h2>Fixing the Table of Contents Overlap</h2>\n<p>The post page layout used a 12-column grid with the article taking <code>lg:col-span-8</code> and the sidebar taking the remaining 4 columns. That math is fine when the sidebar is empty, but here the sidebar holds two stacked panels: the table of contents and the series navigation. Four columns is not enough width for both, especially because the table of contents was not given any minimum width and collapsed around its link text. The series panel and the ToC ended up competing for the same horizontal space, and on posts with long heading text they literally overlapped.</p>\n<p>The fix was two parts.</p>\n<p>First, we switched the grid from a column-count system to a fixed fraction layout:</p>\n<pre><code>lg:grid-cols-[1fr_340px]\n</code></pre>\n<p>This gives the article all available space and fixes the sidebar to 340px. That number is not magical; it is wide enough to hold most heading text without wrapping, and narrow enough to keep the article readable on medium-width screens.</p>\n<p>Second, we gave the ToC its own constrained container. Before, the ToC was soft-styled as just a list without an explicit width. Now it sits inside:</p>\n<pre><code>max-w-[340px]\n</code></pre>\n<p>with padding, a border, and a card background. That makes it visually distinct and guarantees it stops shrinking around its content.</p>\n<p>We also removed the sticky wrapper from the sidebar. Previously both panels were wrapped in <code>lg:sticky lg:top-24</code>, which pinned the pair together as they scrolled. That was causing a stacking context problem where the series panel could collide with the article content on shorter viewports. Removing the sticky behavior lets each panel scroll naturally with the page, and on longer posts that is the simpler, more predictable behavior.</p>\n<h2>Fixing Horizontal Scroll in Code Blocks</h2>\n<p>The second visible defect was narrower. Long code blocks inside post content were being clipped instead of scrollable. The obvious place to look was the prose styling in <code>app/globals.css</code>.</p>\n<p>The existing rule was forcing <code>overflow-x: auto</code> onto <code>.prose pre</code>, but something else in the cascade was overriding it. The actual culprit turned out to be that the <code>.prose pre</code> rule was missing the full Tailwind shorthand and was being trumped by more specific prose styles coming in from the Tailwind typography plugin. The fix was simply to make the overflow rule more explicit:</p>\n<pre><code>overflow-x: auto\n</code></pre>\n<p>applied to <code>.prose pre</code> in a way that wins the cascade. We added it as an explicit utility shorthand inside the existing prose block so it stays visible and intentional. That fixed long line wrapping and single-line tool invalidation without changing any JavaScript.</p>\n<h2>Fixing the Social Floating Footer</h2>\n<p>The third problem was the social footer. It had two links: GitHub and Ko-fi. The GitHub link was correct, but the Ko-fi link was rendering inconsistently across pages. On some pages it appeared, on others it did not.</p>\n<p>The problem was in how the footer component was being included. The site has a global base href injected as a meta tag, and the footer was constructing absolute URLs by hand instead of using that base href. On pages where the runtime <code>window.location</code> matched the expected production URL, the hardcoded absolute links worked. On build-time-generated pages they did not.</p>\n<p>We fixed this by teaching the footer to read the base href from the meta tag at runtime instead of hardcoding. The footer now asks for the base path the same way other components do, and builds its outbound links from that. That makes the footer consistent on every page regardless of how the page was produced.</p>\n<h2>The Follow-Up That Became a Post: Code Quality and the Static Pipeline</h2>\n<p>Once the visible defects were fixed, we looked at the broader state of the blog repo. There were a few smaller issues that had been accumulating for weeks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>the CLI was creating new posts with manual IDs that collided with existing rows;</li>\n<li>generated artifacts under <code>public/data</code> and <code>lib/</code> were drifting because the regeneration step was manual;</li>\n<li>the TypeScript typecheck was running as a bare <code>tsc --noEmit</code> and reporting false positives because the repo lives in an npm workspace;</li>\n<li>the SQLite test helper alias <code>searchPosts</code> conflicted visually with the real production query with the same name.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We addressed each one directly.</p>\n<p>For the CLI collision, we changed the post deletion workflow: the original duplicate post was removed and the replacement post was rewritten with a fresh auto-incremented ID and the correct original date. That keeps the database clean without manual ID management.</p>\n<p>For generated artifacts drift, we added a regeneration step before the build path so <code>posts-index.json</code>, <code>tags.json</code>, <code>post-tags.json</code>, <code>static-posts-generated.ts</code>, the sitemap, and the feeds are all produced deterministically from the current database state. That means a schema change now forces regeneration by construction instead of by memory.</p>\n<p>For the typecheck noise, we switched to the project&#39;s own npm script, which sets the working directory correctly and limits scope to this workspace. Once we did that, TypeScript started reporting real errors again instead of warnings from sibling packages.</p>\n<p>For the test alias confusion, we renamed the SQLite test helper from <code>searchPosts</code> to <code>searchPostsFTSTests</code>. Nothing changed at runtime. What changed was readability: a developer scanning test output can now tell in one glance whether a failure is in production code or the FTS test harness.</p>\n<h2>What We Did Not Fix</h2>\n<p>There is a list of follow-ups we deliberately left alone:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>adding a regenerate-and-test gate to CI that fails the build when checked-in JSON diverges from the database;</li>\n<li>automating sitemap and feed regeneration inside the build script instead of as a separate npm step;</li>\n<li>unifying CLI help text and autocomplete behavior across all command groups.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These are real issues. Choosing not to chase them today was itself a deliberate decision. The cost of chasing every adjacent improvement is losing momentum on the ones that matter most.</p>\n<h2>The Pattern Today</h2>\n<p>The pattern across all three fixes was the same: find the smallest change that makes the behavior match the intent, verify it against the build, and document the decision. The runtime output matters, but so does the ability to open the relevant file in six months and understand why it looks the way it does.</p>\n<p>That is the standard we are trying to hold.</p>\n",
